  title="Investigating the effect that the mass of salt in water has on its specific heat capacity"
>
  <main class="max-w-3xl print:w-full">
    <h1 class="text-center underline font-bold my-5">
      Investigating the effect that the mass of salt in water has on its
      specific heat capacity
    </h1>
    <h2>Introduction</h2>
    <p>
      Have you ever been told to add salt to water to help it to heat faster? Or
      noticed that the time it takes to heat water varies with the amount of
      water you are heating?
    </p>
    <p>
      These ideas may seem basic but are the basis of this IA and the idea of
      specific heat capacity. The heat capacity of an object is defined as the
      amount of thermal energy required to increase that objects temperature by
      1 K (Khan Academy 2021). However, this measurement isn't particularly
      useful because if the amount (mass, volume or moles) of that object
      changes, the heat capacity must be recalculated. The concept of specific
      heat capacity is founded on the assumption that the amount of an substance
      is directly proportional to its heat capacity. Using this assumption,
      specific heat capacity can be defined as the amount of thermal energy
      required to heat one amount unit (1 kilogram, 1 mole, 1 metre cubed) of a
      substance by 1 K (Tsokos 2014). Most commonly, and throughout this IA,
      specific heat capacity refers to the amount of thermal energy required to
      heat 1 kg of a substance by 1 K.
    </p>
    <p>
      After studying specific heat capacity in class, I found myself unsatisfied
      with not knowing why specific heat capacity varies between substances. To
      understand why the specific heat capacity varies between substances, it is
      first helpful to investigate the concept of temperature. Temperature is
      directly proportional to the average random kinetic energy within an
      object (Tsokos 2014). Since this proportionality is so strict, it can be
      said that any other store of energy that isn't random kinetic will
      increase the specific heat capacity. This introduces many factors that can
      affect specific heat capacity, such as chemical bonds. One such factor
      that, according to Richard Feynman, is particularly important, is the
      number of 'degrees of freedom' a given molecule has. Each degree of
      freedom represents a parameter that is required to describe the motion of
      a molecule (LibreTexts 2017). Only some of the energy used to heat a
      substance will go toward degrees of freedom that increase the temperature,
      and the number of degrees of freedom varies between molecules.
    </p>
    <p>
      To investigate specific heat capacity further, I decided to explore sodium
      chloride dissolved in water. I decided to investigate it at different
      concentrations, which led me to my research question:
    </p>
    <p class="italic font-bold">
      How does the mass of sodium chloride dissolved in water affect the
      specific heat capacity of the solution?
    </p>
    <h2>Hypothesis</h2>
    <p>
      This experiment will involve finding the specific heat capacity of
      different salt solutions.
    </p>
    <p>The specific heat capacity formula is the following:</p>
    <h3 class="text-gray-600 text-sm">Equation 1</h3>
    <Math
      latex={String.raw`Q=mc \Delta T`}
      whereList={[
        {
          propertyAsLatex: "Q",
          value: "Energy in",
          unitAsLatex: "J",
        },
        {
          propertyAsLatex: "m",
          value: "Mass of substance in",
          unitAsLatex: "kg",
        },
        {
          propertyAsLatex: "c",
          value: "Specific heat capacity in",
          unitAsLatex: String.raw`J\cdot kg^{-1}\cdot K^{-1}`,
        },
      ]}
    />
    <p>It can be rearranged to find the specific heat capacity:</p>
    <h3 class="text-gray-600 text-sm">Equation 2</h3>
    <Math latex={String.raw`c=\frac{Q}{m \Delta T}`} />
    <p>
      In this experiment, a salt solution is heated and then mixed with a
      substance of known mass and heat capacity. The energy transfer to the
      substance of known mass and heat capacity is calculated using equation 1.
      The mass, temperature change of salt solution and calculated energy
      transfer is substituted into equation 2 to give the specific heat capacity
      of the salt solution. Equation 3 represents this in a single equation.
    </p>
    <h3 class="text-gray-600 text-sm">Equation 3</h3>
    <Math
      latex={String.raw`c_{s}\ =\ \frac{m_{w}c_{w} \Delta T_{w}}{m_{s} \Delta T_{s}}`}
      whereList={[
        {
          propertyAsLatex: String.raw`c_{s}`,
          value: "Specific heat capacity of solution in",
          unitAsLatex: String.raw`J\cdot kg^{-1}\cdot K^{-1}`,
        },
        {
          propertyAsLatex: String.raw`m_{w}`,
          value: "Mass of substance of known specific heat capacity in",
          unitAsLatex: String.raw`kg`,
        },
        {
          propertyAsLatex: String.raw`c_{w}`,
          value: "Specific heat capacity of known substance in ",
          unitAsLatex: String.raw`J\cdot kg^{-1}\cdot K^{-1}`,
        },
        {
          propertyAsLatex: String.raw`\Delta T_{w}`,
          value: "Temperature change of known substance in",
          unitAsLatex: String.raw`K`,
        },
        {
          propertyAsLatex: String.raw`m_{s}`,
          value: "Mass of salt solution in",
          unitAsLatex: String.raw`kg`,
        },
        {
          propertyAsLatex: String.raw`\Delta T_{s}`,
          value: "Temperature change of salt solution in",
          unitAsLatex: String.raw`K`,
        },
      ]}
    />
    <p>
      The equation states an inverse proportionality between the specific heat
      capacity of the solution and the mass of the solution, which will increase
      as salt is added. However, this proportionality may not hold because the
      temperature changes may not be constant. Sodium chloride has a specific
      heat capacity of <InlineMath
        latex={String.raw`864 J \cdot kg^{−1} \cdot K^{−1}`}
      /> (Chase 1998). Given this value, dissolving sodium chloride in water would
      lower its specific heat capacity. If true, a graph of mass of salt against
      the specific heat capacity would have a negative correlation. If the inverse
      proportionality between the specific heat capacity and mass of salt solution
      holds true, the graph of mass of salt dissolved against the inverse of specific
      heat capacity would have a positive, linear correlation. At the Y intercept,
      the mass of salt in the solution would be 0, i.e. the solution would be distilled
      water. The Y intercept on the graph is expected to be the inverse of the specific
      heat capacity of distilled water, <InlineMath
        latex={String.raw`4186 \cdot kg^{−1} \cdot K^{−1}`}
      />
      (Engineering Toolbox n.d.).
    </p>
