    <h2>Method</h2>
    <p>
      Initially, I wanted to pursue an experiment that investigated specific
      heat capacity by heating solutions rather than cooling them down. In order
      to achieve this, I decided to place a heating element in the solution
      along with a thermometer, noting how long the solution took to reach a
      desired temperature. I started this experiment with my control trial of 0
      salt. My method initially appeared accurate. Unfortunately, when I
      performed by second trial using a salt solution, I discovered that the
      solution had undergone electrolysis. Since the changed solution may have
      different thermal properties, I decided look for other ways to find the
      heat capacity. I considered indirectly heating the water but ruled it out
      on the basis of difficulty with the school lab equipment.
    </p>
    <p>
      I abandoned the idea of heating solutions to find their heat capacity and
      began to explore cooling solutions. The below method is the one I
      eventually decided on.
